I had an anxiety attack yesterday and was tempted to take the easy way out. During that moment it was screaming to me.

I just threw them all out tonight, the whole stash.

I'm done, I'm committed, I'm going to make it. Sharing for anyone else in a similar place, you can make it.

It passed and my brain adapted, rebuilding my natural stress response.

I still get anxiety attacks from time to time. I'm still not 100%. But I'm getting there, dealing with things differently, building myself stronger every day. 

Diet and exercise have become my new drugs.

This year I tapered for a month, bit the bullet, and dealt with the anxiety for a very long week.

"I just got lucky, I don't deserve anything, I'm an addict, I'm an imposter, I'm going to lose everything."

I cut myself off completely from the world, feeling only the worst.

I saw the writing on the wall and switched to baclofen (Rx), a similar but less addicting drug.

Between the market swings and pressure to make it I became more dependent until I had to take it 24/7. 

My GABA receptors didn't function normally anymore. I made myself weak.

This went on for years, I was conscious and careful. I studied drugs after all, I am an expert.

But late 2019 I had a stretch of travel meeting people in different cities across the world, back to back to back. I had to constantly be at 110%, and I started to develop tolerance.

I'm home again and I revisited my stash of GABAergics, relaxing drugs.

It started 7 years ago when I tried a "nootropic," phenibut. I aced interviews, presentations and got great sleep when I just couldn't. Once a month.

I tried to be careful, never intentionally abused it. https://t.co/jPtFWxdb3j

Update:

They taste like crap, so we'll keep iterating on em. I can't wait to share this one with the world. https://t.co/R9ZakcFl9X

zk-SNARKs have been used for a while, but I think the crypto economy has now developed enough to find them lucrative for both retail & corporate actors (more on that another day).

Once crypto achieves a scalable privacy layer, a waterfall of cash will pour into the sector.

‚ÄúARK‚Äù stands for ‚Äúargument of knowledge.‚Äù

This simply refers back to the proofs involved being computationally sound.

The ‚Äúprover‚Äù (sender) is using a legitimate, trustworthy form of proof.

The ‚ÄúN‚Äù stands for ‚Äúnon-interactive.‚Äù

This just means the proof is a single message going from the prover to the verifier with no subsequent interaction being necessary.

This benefits the speed of the network.

Fees will make or break a protocol.

Because you don‚Äôt need to send/process a lot of information to transact, they need much less gas than similar privacy protocols.

Cheap, fast, private, the crypto trifecta.

The ‚ÄúS‚Äù in zk-SNARKs stands for ‚Äúsuccinct.‚Äù

All this means is that the protocol doesn‚Äôt need to send a lot of information to prove a transaction.

This drastically improves tx time and reduces gas.

zk = "Zero Knowledge"

zk-SNARKs allow the sender & receiver to generate "proofs" that hide info (balances, sent amts, etc.) in the tx.

So "zero knowledge" is needed to verify the tx.

The tx is still publicly verifiable as sound, but sensitive info about the tx is private.

Protocols that use zk-SNARKS let you send and receive cryptocurrencies anonymously at a faster and cheaper rate than other privacy methods.

I'll break down and simplify each aspect.

Different coins/protocols use a range of different types of cryptography; they each have their own advantages and trade-offs.

Of the many ways private crypto transactions are handled, zk-SNARKs seem the most likely to reach mass adoption (imo).

Here‚Äôs why:

Cryptography is part of what replaces the ‚Äútrusted third-party‚Äù (like banks/gov) so we can send, mine, & generally use cryptocurrency P2P.

To ‚Äúprove‚Äù ownership of assets, your secret private üîë is used in these complex mathematical puzzles.

These puzzles are called ‚Äúproofs.‚Äù

(Experts, please bear with me as I oversimplify things.)

‚ÄúCryptocurrency‚Äù is based on ‚Äúcryptography.‚Äù

Cryptography = complex mathematical puzzles your computer solves to securely send & receive information.

It stands for ‚ÄúZero-Knowledge Succinct Non-Interactive Argument of Knowledge‚Äù

Don‚Äôt worry, you don‚Äôt need to know what any of those words mean.

Being an oracle aggregator, projects can integrate with @fluxprotocol to receive organic data and access any other oracle on that base layer.

It's sort of like a 1inch for data aggregation.

It's very clever.

Validators stake $FLX to provide data to the oracle.

If they provide incorrect data they, and their $, are slashed by other honest validators in the network.

This quickly snuffs out bad data feeds & keeps bad actors from attempting to manipulate data.

.@fluxprotocol is a cross-chain oracle my team is helping fund and support.

They attempt to solve the problem of bad oracle data by aggregating price feeds across many oracles and holding validators financially accountable if they provide wrong data.

A DEX using just a single oracle to save $ exposes traders to serious price manipulation risk, and every oracle requires the execution of multiple smart contracts to pull and provide data.

This costs a lot of gas. ‚õΩÔ∏èüí∏

Some are working on these issues, though:

The DEX must almost constantly "ask" @chainlink, and possibly other oracles too, for the latest price data in order to provide traders with the most up-to-date prices.

Each time Chainlink gets price data, and each time the DEX gets price data from Chainlink, gas fees occur.

You're on a DEX and set the pair you'd like to trade.

To provide you with a price for each of those assets, the DEX "asks" Chainlink what the current prices are.

Chainlink automatically checks the prices of the most liquid CEXs, averages them, and informs the DEX.

The most popular blockchain oracle is @chainlink.

It launched in 2017 and has had a dedicated group of supporters ever since.

Chainlink is today's blue chip, standard, tried & true decentralized oracle. I would guess that every DEX uses Chainlink data in some way.

Rather than delivering "divine" information, crypto oracles provide "exact" information.

For a DEX to provide an "exact" price for an asset you're trading, an oracle would probably combine price data from several sources then average them.

In mythology, oracles transmit information from one plane of reality to another.

In crypto, they do something similar.

A crypto oracle is an automated third-party that provides specific information from the outside world that smart contracts require to execute.

First, a background on the word itself.

In ancient Greek mythology, oracles were "women chosen by the gods through which divine advice would be spoken through them."

You ask the oracle something, and a god would speak through the oracle to deliver divine information. https://t.co/nlznQqbl9e

Oracles are fundamental to DeFi.

Many newcomers don't understand what they are and how they work.

Depending on your risk appetite, you can allocate different %s of capital to tranches at different stages of the waterfall.

I invested in @Waterfalldefi bc imo systems that minimize risk yet allow for exposure to crypto will be too attractive and pull tradfi money like a üß≤

Seniors eat first, getting their consistent yields "filled" before the extra gains/losses flow to the Juniors.

Attached are images that plainly explain what happens to your portfolio in different scenarios.

Read more in-depth on these scenarios here: https://t.co/bt6zKW6Ihf https://t.co/ouL3ii8NDA

There are Junior and Senior tranches.

Junior tranches are baskets of higher-risk higher-yield assets, and Senior tranches are low to medium-risk with low to medium yields.

The "waterfall" concept comes into play with how yield is distributed.

A frontrunner I'm betting on is @Waterfalldefi.

Their tranching system works like a "waterfall."

It's not as complicated as it might sound at first:

In crypto, we can turn a tranching system like this on its head.

Imagine if you could have tranches of tranches.

You could get a "slice" of a diverse range of high-risk high-yield and a slice of low-risk low-yield assets in one place.

Sort of like tranching¬≤

Tranches are useful for reducing risk and stabilizing returns.

Say you invest in a tranche with assets that yield a 3%, 5%, and 10% return, equally weighted.

If the higher-risk 10% yield asset depreciates in value by half, you still end up with a yield of about 4%.

If you're from tradfi, you're familiar with tranches.

If you're a crypto native, you're less likely to have as much experience with them.

"Tranche" is French for "slice," and it refers to a method of portioning things like securities into baskets to reduce risk for investors.

TL;DR:
Options are for hedging.

I made a long-term investment in a particular options AMM.

They're called @PremiaFinance, and my fund invested in the original public sale. Later, we doubled down to support them.

Here's more on them and why.

The reverse is a "put" option. You're paying for the right to sell an asset at a predetermined price until the option expires.

This is kind of like insurance.

You think an asset you hold might crash? Simply buy a put option and you can hedge against that risk.

Useful jargon:

When you would like to buy an asset in the future, but want to lock in today's price, that's called a "call" option.

It's like putting the asset on layaway. You're making a contractual agreement to have the option to buy that asset at a certain price/time.

Here's a situation where you'd use options:

Let's say you suspect a massive move but aren't sure if it will be up or down.

You could buy both a bullish option and a bearish option and only execute the option that's profitable.

The risk ofc is that there may be no big move.

So, instead of buying or selling an asset directly, options allow you to reserve the right to buy or sell a specific asset at a certain price within a certain time frame.

After the expiration date, you no longer have the right to buy/sell at the chosen price (strike price).

Options are a powerful tool for hedging - or risk managing - your positions.

You pay a premium upfront which gives you the right to buy or sell an asset at a specified price (strike price) within a time frame (expiration date).

A lot of you have probably never traded options.
